FILL_CH18 = {
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>After Athens Paul came to Corinth: Corinth was the capital of the Roman province of Achaia and one of the wealthiest cities in the Roman world. Destroyed by Rome in 146 BCE and refounded as a Roman colony by Julius Caesar in 44 BCE, it was a boom town by Paul's visit (ca. 50-52 CE). Its two harbors — Cenchreae (eastern, Aegean) and Lechaion (western, Adriatic) — made it the trans-shipping hub of Greece, attracting a transient, cosmopolitan population with a reputation for commercial vice. Paul's longest urban mission (18 months) took root here.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Aquila, a Jew from Pontus (Black Sea region), and his wife Priscilla had recently come from Italy because Claudius had expelled all Jews from Rome: the Claudius expulsion is confirmed by Suetonius (<em>Claudius</em> 25.4 — 'since the Jews constantly made disturbances at the instigation of Chrestus, he expelled them'). Most scholars date this to 49 CE (Orosius places it in year 9 of Claudius). 'Chrestus' is likely a misspelling of 'Christus' — the disturbance was probably disputes about Jesus in the Roman synagogues. Aquila and Priscilla were thus early Jewish-Christian expellees who carried the faith westward before Paul arrived.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Paul stayed with them and worked as a tentmaker (<em>skenopoios</em>): tentmaking (or more broadly, leatherworking/canvas-working) was a skilled craft that provided income in any major city. Paul's self-support policy in Corinth was deliberate (1 Cor 9:12-18) — it distinguished his proclamation from that of fee-taking sophists and wonder-workers who were common in cities like Corinth. Working with his hands was both economically necessary and a theological statement about the character of apostolic ministry.</p>",
    "4": "<p>He reasoned in the synagogue every Sabbath (<em>dielegeto en tē synagōgē kata pan sabbaton</em>) and persuaded Jews and Greeks: the Corinthian synagogue was the initial mission venue, as in every city. The 'Greeks' (<em>Hellēnas</em>) in the synagogue are the God-fearers — Gentiles attracted to Jewish monotheism and ethics who attended synagogue without formal conversion. This audience of semi-committed Gentiles was Paul's most responsive demographic: they had the OT background to understand his argument without requiring full proselyte commitment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>When Silas and Timothy arrived from Macedonia, Paul was occupied with the word (<em>syneicheto tō logō</em>) and testified to the Jews that Jesus was the Christ: the arrival of Silas and Timothy (from Thessalonica and Beroea) with a financial gift (Phil 4:15; 2 Cor 11:9) freed Paul from tentmaking to devote full time to proclamation. The 'constraint by the word' (<em>syneicheto</em>) — pressed, compelled — reflects Paul's own vocabulary for apostolic compulsion (1 Cor 9:16: 'woe to me if I do not preach the gospel').</p>",
    "6": "<p>When they opposed and reviled him, he shook out his garments and said, 'Your blood be on your own heads' (<em>to haima hymōn epi tēn kephalēn hymōn</em>): the gesture — shaking dust from garments — was a Jewish sign of repudiation (cf. 13:51 — shaking dust from feet). The blood-guilt formula echoes Ezek 33:4-9 (the watchman absolved when he warns and is ignored) and Matt 27:25 (the crowd accepting blood-guilt). Paul declares he has fulfilled his prophetic responsibility to Israel; their rejection transfers moral accountability to them.</p>",
    "7": "<p>He left there and went to the house of a man named Titius Justus, a worshipper of God, whose house was next door to the synagogue (<em>sunomorousan tē synagōgē</em>): the relocation next door is tactical — maximum proximity to the rejected audience. Titius Justus is a Roman name suggesting a freedman or Roman citizen; as a God-fearer, he bridges the Jewish and Gentile worlds. The house-church next to the synagogue creates a social geography of mission: those passing the synagogue see an alternative gathering space for the same God's worship.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Crispus, the synagogue ruler, believed in the Lord with all his household (<em>episteusen tō kyriō syn holō tō oikō autou</em>): the conversion of the synagogue leader was both a theological victory and a social disruption — the institutional head of Paul's rejected audience now joins the rival house-church. Paul baptized Crispus personally (1 Cor 1:14); the household conversion reflects the unit of social solidarity in antiquity — the household converted together under the paterfamilias's decision.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Do not be afraid, but go on speaking and do not be silent' (<em>mē phobou, alla lalei kai mē siōpēsēs</em>): the divine vision during the night reassures Paul at the precise moment when the synagogue rejection might have prompted withdrawal. The threefold command — don't fear, speak, don't be silent — addresses the specific temptation to withdraw from a hostile environment. The divine promise 'for I am with you' echoes the patriarchal and prophetic reassurances (Gen 26:24; Jer 1:8; Isa 41:10) of divine presence amid opposition.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'No one will attack you to harm you, for I have many in this city who are my people' (<em>laos esti moi polys en tē polei tautē</em>): the divine assurance of a large hidden constituency waiting to receive the gospel explains why Paul should stay. The phrase 'my people' (<em>laos</em>) is the LXX covenant-people term; God declares that his election-purposes for Corinth include many not yet in the visible community. Paul's 18-month ministry and the resulting community (with extensive correspondence in 1-2 Corinthians) fulfills the divine vision.</p>",
    "11": "<p>He stayed a year and six months, teaching the word of God among them: eighteen months is Paul's longest recorded stay in any city except Ephesus (three years, 20:31). The Corinthian stay produced the community addressed in 1 Corinthians, 2 Corinthians, and mentioned in Romans. The founding period established the community's character: intellectually diverse, socially stratified (1 Cor 1:26-29 implies some wealthy, most not), and doctrinally unstable — requiring the extensive subsequent correspondence.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The accusation before Gallio — 'this man is persuading people to worship God contrary to the law' (<em>para ton nomon anapeitlhei tous anthrōpous sebesthia ton theon</em>) — frames the complaint as a violation of Roman legal categories. Under Roman law, Jews had recognized legal status (<em>religio licita</em>); a new movement allegedly departing from authorized Judaism would lack this protection. The accusers are trying to get Roman authority to enforce their community boundaries against Paul by characterizing his teaching as illegal religion.</p>",
    "14": "<p>When Paul was about to speak, Gallio said: the proconsul's intervention before Paul can defend himself is legally significant. Gallio cuts off the speech because he has already determined the legal category of the complaint. His ruling — 'if it were a matter of wrongdoing or vicious crime' — establishes the threshold for Roman judicial intervention: crimes against persons or property. Theological disputes within Judaism do not meet this threshold.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Since it is a matter of questions about words and names and your own law, see to it yourselves — I refuse to be a judge of these things' (<em>kritēs egō toutōn ou boulomai einai</em>): Gallio's ruling establishes an important precedent for the Pauline mission: Roman authority declines jurisdiction over Jewish-Christian theological disputes. This is the same ruling pattern that Festus and Agrippa will apply to Paul in 25:18-19 and 26:31-32. Luke's repeated documentation of Roman non-intervention is a sustained argument for the Christianity's legal legitimacy.</p>",
    "16": "<p>He drove them from the tribunal (<em>apelasen autous apo tou bēmatos</em>): Gallio's physical dismissal — expelling the accusers from the judgment platform — is a humiliation for the synagogue leadership. The <em>bēma</em> (judgment seat) in the Corinthian agora has been archaeologically identified; a limestone platform in the center of the city's civic space served as the governor's public court. Gallio's decision is made in the most public possible setting.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Then they all seized Sosthenes, the synagogue ruler, and beat him in front of the tribunal, and Gallio paid no attention (<em>ouden toutōn tō Galliōni emelen</em>): Sosthenes's beating is variously interpreted — either the crowd venting frustration at the failed prosecution (Greek mob anti-Semitism), or Jews beating Sosthenes as punishment for the failed case, or believers taking revenge. A Sosthenes appears in 1 Cor 1:1 as Paul's co-author — possibly this same figure, later converted. Gallio's indifference is the pointed end of the judicial narrative: Roman authority neither helps nor hinders the mission.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Paul stayed many more days in Corinth, then took leave of the brothers and sailed for Syria with Priscilla and Aquila. At Cenchreae he had cut his hair (<em>keiramenos... tēn kephalēn</em>) for he was under a vow (<em>eucHēn</em>): the vow-completion at Cenchreae (Corinth's eastern harbor) connects Paul's Corinthian ministry to a Nazirite-type vow (Num 6). Paul's maintenance of Jewish religious practices alongside his Gentile-inclusion theology reflects his 'to the Jew I became as a Jew' flexibility (1 Cor 9:20). Priscilla and Aquila's inclusion in the travel party begins their Ephesian chapter.</p>",
    "19": "<p>They came to Ephesus, and he left Priscilla and Aquila there, while he himself entered the synagogue and reasoned with the Jews (<em>dielegeto tois Ioudaiois</em>): Ephesus was the provincial capital of Asia and Paul's eventual three-year base (20:31). The brief visit on this occasion is a scouting and community-planting stop — Priscilla and Aquila remain to establish the community that Paul will later return to develop. Their presence in Ephesus (1 Cor 16:19) is the foundation Paul builds on in 19:1-41.</p>",
    "20": "<p>When they asked him to stay longer (<em>erotōntōn autōn epi pleiDna chronon meinai</em>), he declined: the synagogue's positive response to Paul's initial teaching contrasts with the hostile reception in Corinth and other cities. The Ephesian synagogue invitation to remain is a rare positive signal; Paul's refusal is explained by the commitment in v.21. The Ephesian community's receptiveness anticipates the extended ministry of chapter 19.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'I must by all means keep the coming feast at Jerusalem' (<em>dei me pantōs tēn eortēn tēn erchomenēn poiēsai eis Hierosolyma</em>): the festival obligation (likely Passover or Pentecost) reflects Paul's continued participation in Jewish pilgrimage practice. His return to the Jerusalem-Antioch home base between journeys (the end of the second journey, beginning of the third) follows the same return-arc pattern as the first journey (14:26-28). Jerusalem is both the theological center and the source of apostolic accountability.</p>",
    "22": "<p>When he had landed at Caesarea, he went up and greeted the church (<em>anabas kai aspAsamenos tēn ekklēsian</em>) and then went down to Antioch: the compressed summary of the Jerusalem visit (implied by 'went up' — the standard term for ascending to Jerusalem) and Antioch return marks the end of the second journey. The formal greeting of the Jerusalem church maintains the apostolic relationship; the Antioch base provides the launch platform for the third journey. Luke's rapid summary keeps the narrative pace without dwelling on inter-journey transitions.</p>",
    "23": "<p>After spending some time in Antioch, Paul went through the region of Galatia and Phrygia, strengthening all the disciples (<em>epistērizōn pantas tous mathētas</em>): the third journey begins with the same pastoral re-visitation pattern as the second (15:41). The Galatian-Phrygian route covers the first-journey communities (Derbe, Lystra, Iconium, Pisidian Antioch) plus the second-journey additions (Philippi, Thessalonica, Beroea were on the second journey; the third journey apparently revisits Asia Minor first). The 'strengthening' vocabulary is Paul's consistent return-visit priority.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A Jew named Apollos, a native of Alexandria, came to Ephesus. He was an eloquent man (<em>anēr logios</em>), competent in the Scriptures: Apollos represents the Alexandrian Jewish intellectual tradition — the same milieu that produced Philo's biblical philosophy. <em>Logios</em> (eloquent, learned) is the vocabulary of high Hellenistic education; Apollos was an educated rhetor as well as a scriptural exegete. Alexandria had the largest Jewish population in the diaspora and an intense tradition of Greek-Jewish intellectual synthesis. Apollos brings this tradition into the church.</p>",
    "25": "<p>He had been instructed in the way of the Lord (<em>kateEchēmenos tēn hodon tou kyriou</em>), and being fervent in spirit he spoke and taught accurately the things concerning Jesus, though he knew only the baptism of John: Apollos's instruction 'in the way of the Lord' was apparently complete enough for accurate teaching about Jesus but incomplete regarding the Spirit-baptism. He represents the overlap zone between the Baptist movement and the church — those who knew Jesus's teaching (possibly from witnesses in Alexandria) but had not received the post-Pentecost Spirit. His fervent spirit is authentic even while his understanding is partial.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Priscilla and Aquila heard him and took him aside (<em>proselabonto auton</em>) and explained to him the way of God more accurately (<em>akribesterDon autō exetheInto tēn tou theou hodon</em>): the marital pair's role in completing Apollos's theological education is a significant detail — a woman (Priscilla named first, suggesting her prominence) provides doctrinal instruction to a gifted male teacher. The private, non-public correction respects Apollos's dignity while addressing the gap. The model is pastoral wisdom: supplement rather than publicly correct.</p>",
    "27": "<p>When he wished to cross to Achaia (<em>dielthein eis tēn Achaian</em>), the brothers encouraged him and wrote to the disciples to welcome him (<em>apodexasthai auton</em>): the letter of commendation from the Ephesian church to Corinth (<em>cheirograph</em>ia) is the standard Hellenistic practice for introducing trusted travelers to new communities. Paul refers to letters of recommendation in 2 Cor 3:1 — the practice was universal. Apollos's reception in Corinth and his powerful refutation of the Jews there (v.28) established him as a major figure alongside Peter and Paul (1 Cor 1:12; 3:4-6).</p>",
    "28": "<p>He powerfully refuted the Jews in public (<em>diakatalenkhomenos tous Ioudaious dēmosia</em>), demonstrating by the Scriptures that the Christ was Jesus: Apollos's method is scriptural demonstration — <em>epideiknys dia tōn graphōn</em> (showing through the Scriptures). His Alexandrian background would have given him mastery of both the Greek OT and the allegorical-typological methods of interpretation. His public synagogue debates represent the same pattern as Paul's but with the specific rhetorical skills of the Alexandrian tradition added to the apostolic proclamation.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH19 = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>While Apollos was at Corinth, Paul passed through the inland country and came to Ephesus: the 'inland country' (<em>ta anōterika merē</em>) is the highland route through Phrygia and Galatia rather than the coastal road — consistent with the strengthening visits of 18:23. Ephesus (modern Selçuk, Turkey) was the premier city of Roman Asia, population estimated at 200,000-500,000, with the Artemis temple as its defining monument and tourism industry. Paul's three-year Ephesian ministry (20:31) was the longest continuous urban mission in Acts.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Finding some disciples (<em>mathētas</em>) who had not heard there is a Holy Spirit: the dozen 'disciples' (v.7) in Ephesus parallel the Samaritan situation of Acts 8 — baptized believers without evident Spirit-reception. Their description as disciples of John (v.3) and their ignorance of the Spirit identifies them as the easternmost extension of the Baptist movement. John's ministry in Judea produced communities that spread through the diaspora without the Pentecost developments; these twelve represent one such pocket community.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Into what then were you baptized?' — Paul's diagnostic question reveals the theological gap: John's baptism was preparatory (for repentance, in anticipation of the Coming One) while Christian baptism is in the name of Jesus and carries Spirit-reception. The distinction between these two forms of initiation was important enough in the early church that Luke documents it three times: the Samaritan situation (8:14-17), Apollos (18:25-26), and these Ephesian twelve. The Spirit is the mark of the new era, not just a supplement to proper procedure.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'John baptized with the baptism of repentance (<em>baptisma metanoias</em>), telling the people to believe in the one who was to come after him, that is, Jesus' — Paul's explanation grounds John's baptism as genuine but anticipatory. The Baptist himself had pointed to a successor ('one coming after me, the strap of whose sandals I am not worthy to untie'); his baptism was calibrated to that expectation. Those who had received John's baptism had been rightly oriented toward Jesus but had not yet encountered the fulfillment of what John promised.</p>",
    "5": "<p>On hearing this they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus (<em>eis to onoma tou kyriou Iēsou</em>): the rebaptism of those who had only John's baptism establishes that Christian baptism is distinct from and cannot be collapsed into John's. The 'name of the Lord Jesus' formula (used in Acts in several variations: 2:38; 8:16; 10:48; 19:5) identifies the mediating authority under which the baptism is performed — the risen Christ whose name is invoked. The immediate sequence of baptism then laying on of hands follows the Samaritan pattern.</p>",
    "6": "<p>When Paul had laid his hands on them, the Holy Spirit came on them (<em>ēlthen to pneuma to hagion ep autous</em>) and they began speaking in tongues and prophesying: the arrival of the Spirit with immediate charismata mirrors Pentecost (Acts 2) and Cornelius's household (10:44-46). The consistent pattern across these boundary-crossing moments — Spirit arriving with visible/audible manifestation — is Luke's theological signature: each major expansion of the community has its own miniature Pentecost authenticating the inclusion. The twelve Ephesians are the last such group in Acts.</p>",
    "7": "<p>There were about twelve men in all (<em>hōsei andres dōdeka</em>): the twelve is likely not accidental — the number echoes the Twelve apostles and symbolically represents a restored Israel community. The Ephesian twelve receive the Spirit and begin the community that will become one of the most significant in early Christianity (the Johannine community, according to tradition, was centered in Ephesus; the seven churches of Revelation include the Ephesian church as first-addressed).</p>",
    "8": "<p>He entered the synagogue and for three months spoke boldly (<em>parrēsiazomenos</em>), reasoning and persuading about the kingdom of God (<em>peri tēs basileias tou theou</em>): three months of synagogue engagement before expulsion is the longest synagogue run in Acts (cf. three Sabbaths in Thessalonica, 17:2). The 'kingdom of God' as the topic — Paul's preaching in Acts consistently centers on the kingdom (28:23, 31) — reflects the continuity between Jesus's proclamation and the apostolic message. The Ephesian community's extended receptivity made Ephesus Paul's most productive base.</p>",
    "9": "<p>When some became stubborn and continued in unbelief, speaking evil of the Way before the congregation, he withdrew from them and took the disciples with him, reasoning daily in the hall of Tyrannus (<em>tē scholē Tyrannōu</em>): <em>scholē</em> is the Greek word for a school — a lecture hall or space used for philosophical teaching. Tyrannus (possibly a local philosopher or teacher who rented out space) provided the venue Paul used for daily instruction. One Western text adds 'from the fifth to the tenth hour' (11am-4pm) — the midday hours when schools were typically idle, Paul using the space during its off-peak period.</p>",
    "10": "<p>This continued for two years, so that all the residents of Asia heard the word of the Lord, both Jews and Greeks (<em>pantas tous katoikountas tēn Asian akousai ton logon tou kyriou</em>): the two years of daily teaching in the Tyrannean hall produced a regional missionary effect: the seven churches of Revelation (Smyrna, Pergamum, Thyatira, Sardis, Philadelphia, Laodicea — all in Asia province) were probably founded during or as a result of this period, as were Colossae and Hierapolis (Col 1:2, 7 implies Epaphras evangelized Colossae, presumably trained or deployed from Ephesus).</p>",
    "11": "<p>God was doing extraordinary miracles (<em>dynameis ou tas tychousas</em>) by the hands of Paul: <em>ou tas tychousas</em> (not ordinary/not the common sort) is litotes — these were unusual even by the standard of apostolic signs. The textual description — handkerchiefs and aprons from Paul's body being carried to the sick — reflects the ancient belief in the transferability of a holy person's power through physical contact (cf. the woman with hemorrhage touching Jesus's garment, Luke 8:44; Peter's shadow healing, Acts 5:15).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Handkerchiefs (<em>soudaria</em>) or aprons (<em>simikinthia</em>) that had touched his skin were carried away to the sick (<em>apopheresthai apo tou chrōtos autou soudaria ē simikinthia kai apallassesthai ap autōn tas nosous</em>): <em>soudaria</em> is the Latinism for sweat-cloths (face-cloths); <em>simikinthia</em> are workman's aprons — consistent with Paul's tentmaking practice. The healing through contact-objects created a demand for Paul's personal effects as healing media, which became the occasion for the exorcist fraud of vv.13-16.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Some itinerant Jewish exorcists (<em>tines tōn perierchomenōn Ioudaiōn exorkistōn</em>): Jewish professional exorcists were attested in antiquity (Josephus, <em>Ant.</em> 8.45-47 — describes exorcistic techniques attributed to Solomon; the Testament of Solomon is an elaborate magical manual). The Ephesus magical papyri (<em>Papyri Graecae Magicae</em>) document the rich magical tradition of the city. These exorcists attempted to appropriate Paul's Jesus-name formula as a more powerful tool — treating the name of Jesus as a ritual invocation like other names of power in magical practice.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Seven sons of Sceva, a Jewish chief priest (<em>archiereōs Ioudaiou</em>), were doing this: 'chief priest' may be an informal title for a senior priestly family rather than the actual High Priest (no Sceva is known from high-priestly lists). Seven sons practicing exorcism together is a business arrangement — the family exorcism trade. Their attempt to use the formula 'I adjure you by the Jesus whom Paul proclaims' reveals that they recognize Paul's authority as derived from Jesus without understanding what that authority actually entails.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Jesus I know, and Paul I recognize, but who are you?' (<em>ton men Iēsoun ginōskō kai ton Paulon epistamai, hymeis de tines este</em>): the evil spirit's response makes the theological point with brutal comedy: genuine spiritual authority is personal and relational, not formulaic and transferable. The demon acknowledges Jesus and Paul as known quantities — their authority is authentic. The exorcists' lack of this relationship makes their formula empty; they are strangers to the power they are trying to invoke.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The man in whom was the evil spirit leaped on them, overpowered them all, and escaped from that house naked and wounded (<em>gymnus kai tetFaumatismenous ekphugoIn ek tou oikou ekeinou</em>): 'all' of them (<em>amphoteron</em> in some texts, suggesting two; <em>pantōn</em> in others, suggesting all seven) — overpowered by a single possessed man. The physical humiliation of the exorcists — stripped and wounded, fleeing — provides vivid evidence that the Jesus-name is not a magic formula but a personal authority. The narrative would have circulated rapidly in Ephesus's magical-practitioner community.</p>",
    "17": "<p>This became known to all the residents of Ephesus, Jews and Greeks, and fear fell on them all (<em>epepesen phobos epi pantas autous</em>) and the name of the Lord Jesus was extolled (<em>emegalyneto to onoma tou kyriou Iēsou</em>): the community's response connects fear and honor. The episode distinguishes authentic from fraudulent use of Jesus's name precisely by the failure of the fraudulent attempt; the name's power is vindicated by its non-transferability to unauthorized users. This becomes the occasion for the community's self-purification in vv.18-20.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Many of those who were now believers came confessing and divulging their practices (<em>exaggellontes tas praxeis autōn</em>): the confessional disclosure of magical practices by new converts reflects the community's understanding that belonging to Christ required renunciation of the magical world. The confession is corporate — 'many who were now believers' had apparently maintained dual practice after initial conversion. The Sceva episode is the trigger for genuine repentance that purges this syncretism.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A number of those who had practiced magic arts brought their books together and burned them in the sight of all (<em>katekaiOn enōpion pantōn</em>), and they calculated the value of them and found it came to fifty thousand pieces of silver (<em>drachmas myriadas pente</em>): fifty thousand drachmas was approximately fifty thousand days' wages for a laborer — an enormous sum. The Ephesian magical papyri found by archaeologists give a sense of the genre: lengthy, expensive texts combining Jewish, Egyptian, and Greek divine names in complex ritual formulae. Their public burning signaled complete repudiation of the magical system.</p>",
    "20": "<p>So the word of the Lord continued to increase and prevail mightily (<em>houtōs kata kratos tou kyriou ho logos ēuxanen kai ischyen</em>): the summary formula marks the completion of the Ephesian mission's first phase and closes Acts' third major sequence. <em>Kata kratos</em> (with force/mightily) is the strongest growth formula in Acts' six summary statements (6:7; 9:31; 12:24; 16:5; 19:20; 28:31). The burning of the magical books — renunciation of the rival spiritual system — is the soil from which the mighty growth emerges.</p>",
    "21": "<p>After these events Paul resolved in the Spirit (<em>etheto en tō pneumati ho Paulos</em>) to pass through Macedonia and Achaia and go to Jerusalem, saying, 'After I have been there, I must also see Rome' (<em>dei me kai Rōmēn idein</em>): the itinerary planning moment is both strategic and pneumatic — 'resolved in the Spirit' is a Lukan phrase for Spirit-guided decision. The Rome vision is the first in Acts; 23:11 will confirm it as divine purpose: 'you must testify also in Rome'. Paul's letter to Rome (Romans, written from Corinth ca. 57 CE) is the theological preparation for a visit he plans as a missionary base for Spain (Rom 15:24-28).</p>",
    "22": "<p>He sent into Macedonia two of his helpers, Timothy and Erastus (<em>Timotheou kai Eraston</em>), while he himself stayed in Asia for a while: Timothy is Paul's established co-worker since the second journey; Erastus appears in Rom 16:23 as 'the city treasurer' of Corinth, suggesting a person of social standing who travels with Paul. The advance party to Macedonia prepares for Paul's own journey (20:1-2) through the churches there. The two-person sending pattern reflects both Jewish testimony requirements and practical travel security.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Demetrius, a silversmith who made silver shrines of Artemis, brought no little business to the craftsmen (<em>pareicheto tois technItais ouk oligēn ergasian</em>): the Artemis cult was Ephesus's primary industry — the temple was a tourist destination, treasury, and civic identity center. Silver miniature temples (<em>naous argyrous</em>) were votive offerings and souvenirs; their production was a major economic sector. Demetrius represents the guild leadership of a craft industry whose livelihood was directly threatened by the gospel's advance (cf. Acts 16:16-19 — the fortune-telling slave in Philippi).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Men, you know that from this business we have our wealth' (<em>ek tautēs tēs ergasias hē euporia hēmin estin</em>): Demetrius's speech frankly acknowledges the economic motivation alongside the religious one. The guild meeting (summoning craftsmen and related workers) is a collegium gathering — the professional trade associations of the Roman world had religious, social, and economic functions bound together. The appeal to economic interest is the politically honest core of the riot's instigation, though the religious language (v.27) provides its public legitimacy.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'This Paul has persuaded and turned away a great many people, saying that gods made with hands are not gods' (<em>legōn hoti ouk eisin theoi hoi dia cheirōn ginomenoi</em>): the anti-idol formulation echoes the prophetic polemic (Isa 44:9-20; Jer 10:3-5; Ps 115:4-8). Paul's proclamation in Ephesus apparently included direct critique of idol manufacture — not merely positive proclamation but negative argument against the theological category that made Demetrius's business meaningful. The 'not only in Ephesus but in almost all of Asia' spread shows the regional impact of the Ephesian mission.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Not only is there danger that this trade of ours may come into disrepute (<em>eis apelegmon elthein</em>), but also that the temple of the great goddess Artemis may be counted as nothing' (<em>eis outhen logisthēnai</em>): the Artemis temple was more than a religious site — it was the greatest bank in western Anatolia (holding deposits from cities and kings), a major employer through tourism and craft industries, and the supreme symbol of Ephesian civic identity. The threat to Artemis's honor was a threat to the city's self-understanding; Demetrius's appeal to civic pride is more powerful than his appeal to economic interest.</p>",
    "28": "<p>When they heard this they were enraged and were crying out, 'Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!' (<em>megalē hē Artemis Ephesiōn</em>): the cultic acclamation was a standard liturgical shout — inscriptions from Ephesus preserve this exact formula as a temple dedication. The crowd's eruption from a guild meeting into a city-wide riot shows how quickly artisanal economic grievance could mobilize civic religious identity. The theater (seating ~24,000) was the venue for civic assemblies (<em>ekklēsia</em>) — appropriate for the crisis that the city's identity is under threat.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The city was filled with the confusion (<em>synchuseōs</em>) and they rushed together into the theater, dragging with them Gaius and Aristarchus, Macedonians who were Paul's travel companions: Gaius and Aristarchus (Col 4:10 identifies Aristarchus as a Thessalonian co-prisoner of Paul) are seized as surrogates when Paul himself cannot be found or is protected. The theater was the civic assembly space of Ephesus — a political <em>ekklēsia</em> turned into a mob. Luke's use of <em>ekklēsia</em> for both the Christian assembly and this civic gathering (v.39) is probably intentional contrast.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Paul wished to go in to the crowd (<em>boulomenou de tou Paulou eiselthein eis ton dēmon</em>), but the disciples would not let him (<em>ouk eiōn auton hoi mathētai</em>): Paul's impulse to address the crowd directly is characteristic — his boldness in hostile situations (9:29; 22:1) would put him at serious personal risk in an anti-Paul mob. The disciples' restraint is the community's protective care for its founder. Even 'some of the Asiarchs who were his friends sent to him and were urging him not to venture into the theater' — a remarkable detail showing Paul had cultivated relationships with senior Roman-appointed provincial officials.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Some of the Asiarchs (<em>Asiarchai</em>) who were his friends sent to him: the Asiarchs were the leading civic officials of the Asian province — wealthy, romanized provincials who presided over the imperial cult and provincial games. Their friendship with Paul shows that his Ephesian mission had reached the highest social levels of the city, not just the artisan and synagogue communities. The Asiarchs' warning reflects both personal concern and their own interest in preventing disorder that could embarrass the province before Rome.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Now some cried out one thing, some another, for the assembly was in confusion (<em>en sugkechymenē hē ekklēsia</em>), and most of them did not know why they had come together: the theater's chaotic condition — most participants not knowing what the gathering was about — is realistic. Ancient mob scenes were frequently characterized by contagious energy without coherent purpose. Luke's detail about the confusion is both realistic and ironic: the 'great is Artemis' crowd is as confused as any disorganized mob.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Some of the crowd prompted Alexander, whom the Jews had put forward (<em>probAlantown ton Alexandron hoi Ioudaioi</em>): the Jewish community's attempt to distance themselves from Paul (by putting forward a spokesman to disclaim connection) shows the diaspora Jews' vulnerability — they could be targeted alongside the Christians by an anti-monotheist crowd. Alexander's attempt to speak is silenced by the crowd's recognition that he was a Jew; the anti-idol stance of Judaism made the Jewish community a secondary target of Artemis-cult loyalty.</p>",
    "34": "<p>For about two hours they kept shouting, 'Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!' (<em>megalē hē Artemis Ephesiōn</em>): two hours of chanting the cultic acclamation is historically credible — ancient civic assemblies and mob gatherings could sustain rhythmic chanting for extended periods. The shout simultaneously expressed religious loyalty, civic identity, economic anxiety, and social bonding. Archaeological inscriptions confirm the formula; Luke's documentation of it is consistent with the epigraphic record.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The town clerk (<em>grammateus</em>) quieted the crowd and said, 'Men of Ephesus, who is there who does not know that the city of the Ephesians is temple keeper (<em>neōkoron</em>) of the great Artemis and of the sacred stone that fell from the sky?': the <em>grammateus</em> was the most important civic official in a Greek city — the secretary who managed public records and communications with the Roman governor. His intervention is the legal voice of civic order. <em>Neōkoron</em> (temple warden) was Ephesus's official title, confirmed by coins and inscriptions — it was the city's proudest identity marker. The sacred stone (<em>diopetous</em>, fell from Zeus) may refer to a meteorite housed in the temple.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Seeing then that these things cannot be denied, you ought to be quiet (<em>katestellenous hyparkhein hymas ēsychazein dei</em>) and do nothing rash' — the town clerk's appeal to the unquestionable nature of Artemis's greatness is the rhetorical strategy of dismissing the threat to neutralize the riot. If Artemis's greatness cannot be challenged, then the Christians' preaching poses no real threat worth rioting about. The argument is political logic: overreacting to a minor religious nuisance creates more danger (Roman intervention) than the nuisance itself.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'You have brought these men here who are neither temple robbers (<em>hierosylous</em>) nor blasphemers of our goddess' (<em>blasphēmountas tēn theon hēmōn</em>): the town clerk's legal verdict is the fourth such exoneration in Acts' judicial sequence (cf. Gallio's ruling, 18:14-15; Festus, 25:18-19; Agrippa, 26:31-32). Luke's consistent documentation of Roman and civic officials declaring the Christians innocent of actionable offenses is his sustained defense of Christianity's legal legitimacy. The specific charges — temple robbery and blasphemy — are the most serious that could be brought in an Artemis-city context.</p>",
    "38": "<p>If Demetrius and the craftsmen have a complaint against anyone, the courts are open (<em>agoraioi agontai kai anthupatoi eisin</em>) and there are proconsuls — let them bring charges against one another: the town clerk redirects the guild's complaint to the proper legal channel — the courts and proconsuls of the Roman province. The appeal to proper legal procedure is both civic wisdom and political self-protection: if the riot leads to Roman intervention, Ephesian civic officials will be held accountable. The reference to proconsuls (plural) may be an error or reflect multiple deputies.</p>",
    "39": "<p>If you seek anything further, it shall be settled in the regular assembly (<em>en tē ennomō ekklēsia</em>, the lawful/regular assembly): the contrast between the current <em>ekklēsia</em> (mob assembly) and the <em>ennomos ekklēsia</em> (legally constituted assembly) distinguishes legitimate civic deliberation from riot. The regular assembly met three times a month in Ephesus by constitutional prescription; its decisions had legal standing. The town clerk is insisting that civic governance requires proper procedure — the mob has no legal authority to decide anything.</p>",
    "40": "<p>'For we really are in danger of being charged with rioting today (<em>enstaseos peri tēs sēmeron egkaleisthai staseōs</em>), there being no cause that we can give to justify this commotion' — the town clerk's concern about Roman investigation is the political clincher. Provincial cities that generated riots came under Roman scrutiny; civic officials who failed to maintain order could face sanctions. His intervention is ultimately self-protective civic management, but the providential effect is Paul's protection. The Roman administrative system again unwittingly serves the mission's preservation.</p>",
    "41": "<p>And when he had said these things, he dismissed the assembly (<em>apelysen tēn ekklēsian</em>): the town clerk's formal dismissal restores civic order. Luke's narrative of the Ephesian riot is the most detailed civic disturbance scene in Acts — richer in specific detail than even the Jerusalem crowd scenes. Its resolution through civic procedure rather than Roman military intervention or apostolic miracle is Luke's pointed demonstration that the gospel does not require special pleading or divine rescue from every crisis; ordinary civil order, rightly invoked, can protect the mission.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH18)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH19)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'acts', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Acts mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
